<div id="review_2262787324" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2262787324" />
    <a title="Maine Colonial" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2697302-maine-colonial"><img alt="Maine Colonial" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1532816545p2/2697302.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2262787324?book_show_action=true">Jan 23, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Maine Colonial" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Maine Colonial" href="/user/show/2697302-maine-colonial">Maine Colonial</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audiobook 9781473668348" href="/book/show/38093311-winter-solstice">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2697302-maine-colonial?shelf=coming-of-age">coming-of-age</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2697302-maine-colonial?shelf=being-or-getting-old">being-or-getting-old</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2697302-maine-colonial?shelf=novel">novel</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2697302-maine-colonial?shelf=british">british</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2697302-maine-colonial?shelf=memorable">memorable</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2697302-maine-colonial?shelf=favorite-authors">favorite-authors</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2697302-maine-colonial?shelf=re-read">re-read</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2262787324" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5755484198689268695">You know how the Danish concept of hygge (coziness, comfort, conviviality) has been popular lately? Well, Rosamunde Pilcher was all over that stuff years ago. Her novels have always celebrated the simple beauties and pleasures of ever-changing weather, warming a home with friends, family, food and drink, overcoming pain to re-find love. Her books are what I consider to be the ultimate comfort reads, and Winter Solstice is just what you should be reading if you’re trying the hygge lifestyle this </span>
  <span id="freeText5755484198689268695" style="display:none">You know how the Danish concept of hygge (coziness, comfort, conviviality) has been popular lately? Well, Rosamunde Pilcher was all over that stuff years ago. Her novels have always celebrated the simple beauties and pleasures of ever-changing weather, warming a home with friends, family, food and drink, overcoming pain to re-find love. Her books are what I consider to be the ultimate comfort reads, and Winter Solstice is just what you should be reading if you’re trying the hygge lifestyle this winter.<br /><br />My favorite Pilcher book is Winter Solstice. I re-read it pretty much every December to remind myself that there is beauty and warmth even in the shortest, coldest days of the year. This year, an unabridged audio version of the book finally became available and I snapped it up for my re-read. (For some reason, it was issued in January, not December, which seems just so wrong, but the days are still short and listening this month, in the sometime bleak midwinter, was a real pleasure.)<br /><br />In Winter Solstice, Elfrida Phipps is the magnet for an assortment of heartsore characters. Elfrida is a 62-year-old retired actress who is herself not far removed from the sadness of the death of her love, but her always-optimistic character adapts by moving from London to a Hampshire village and immediately making a new life with a shelter dog, Horace, and a new circle of friends. Since the book description reveals it, it’s not a spoiler to say that this new life is turned upside down, resulting in Elfrida suddenly moving to the far north of Scotland with a grief-stricken friend, only weeks before the shortest day of the year.<br /><br />What was supposed to be two oldsters holed up in sadness and solitude turns into something entirely different, as an assortment of younger characters join them, bringing life back, and optimism for the future. That sentence makes it sound like this is some kind of sentimental or spiritual book, but that’s not really it. So much of it is about everyday life, like cleaning a disused house, buying furniture, appliances and groceries, planning meals, Christmas shopping. And it’s not all sweetness and light, either. Elfrida’s young cousins have to deal with their extremely selfish relatives, and the main characters aren’t saints themselves. That makes them relatable and makes the book both magical and grounded.<br /><br />It occurs to me that the appeal of a Pilcher book is that it's about solving practical and emotional problems. Her characters find solutions to everything from how to dress a festive table when you have no tablecloths to how to outsmart an impossible relative and make everyone come away feeling a winner. I've read that the reason why women like mysteries is because of the problem-solving element. (Nobody explained <i>why</i> problem solving particularly appeals to women, but I'm willing to accept the premise.) Pilcher books have that in spades, so I think they're a good choice for the mystery reader looking for a palate-cleanser book.<br /><br />I’m seriously thinking of listening to the book over again right away.<br /><br /><u>December 30, 2020</u>. I just finished my annual re-read, and it was delightful, as always. It's funny how you notice different things from year to year, though. This year, I’m conscious of some incidents of mansplaining!<br /><br />On the positive side, I realized that one thing that’s so appealing about Rosamunde Pilcher books is that her characters are often able to pick up and move their whole lives without much effort. They can pack up a small car and go, and yet seem to have all they need. Isn’t that a wonderful prospect? </span>
  <a data-text-id="5755484198689268695" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


